# Helper function (adapted to your column names)
read_epa <- function(path) {
  df <- readr::read_csv(path, show_col_types = FALSE) |>
    janitor::clean_names()

  df |>
    dplyr::transmute(
      date      = lubridate::ymd(date),
      pm25      = daily_mean_pm2_5_concentration,
      state     = state,
      county    = county,
      city      = local_site_name,
      site_id   = as.character(site_id),
      latitude  = site_latitude,
      longitude = site_longitude
    )
}

##Summary statistics show that in 2002, PM2.5 concentrations ranged from 0.0 to 104.3 µg/m³, with a median of 12.0 µg/m³ and a mean of 16.1 µg/m³. In 2022, the range was wider (up to 302.5 µg/m³), but the overall distribution was shifted toward lower values, with a median of 6.8 µg/m³ and a mean of 8.4 µg/m³. This suggests that although extreme outliers exist in 2022, typical daily concentrations were substantially lower than in 2002.##
##The histograms support these findings. The 2002 distribution is right-skewed with a long tail extending above 80 µg/m³, indicating frequent moderate pollution events and occasional severe ones. In contrast, the 2022 distribution is tightly concentrated at lower levels, with the majority of observations below 15 µg/m³. Only a small number of extreme spikes above 100 µg/m³ appear in 2022, which are likely isolated events such as wildfire episodes.##

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(janitor)
library(lubridate)

# Define a custom reader for EPA data
read_epa <- function(path) {
  # Read all columns as character
  raw <- readr::read_csv(
    path,
    col_types = readr::cols(.default = readr::col_character()),
    show_col_types = FALSE
  ) |> janitor::clean_names()

  # Parse date
  dates <- suppressWarnings(mdy(raw$date))
  if (mean(is.na(dates)) > 0.5) {
    dates <- suppressWarnings(ymd(raw$date))
  }

  tibble(
    date      = as.Date(dates),
    pm25      = as.numeric(raw$daily_mean_pm2_5_concentration),
    state     = raw$state,
    county    = raw$county,
    city      = raw$local_site_name,
    site_id   = raw$site_id,
    latitude  = as.numeric(raw$site_latitude),
    longitude = as.numeric(raw$site_longitude)
  )
}

# Combine and clean
pm_all <- bind_rows(
  pm_2002_raw %>% mutate(year = 2002L),
  pm_2022_raw %>% mutate(year = 2022L)
) %>%
  transmute(
    date,
    year  = as.integer(year),   # Year identifier
    pm    = pm25,               # Simplified name for PM2.5
    state = factor(state),
    county= factor(county),
    city  = factor(city),
    site  = site_id,
    lat   = latitude,
    lon   = longitude
  )

library(dplyr)

# Define a reasonable range for PM2.5 (commonly 0 ~ 500 µg/m³, values outside are implausible)
pm_all <- pm_all %>%
  mutate(
    pm_invalid = is.na(pm) | pm < 0 | pm > 500
  )

# Calculate the proportion of missing/implausible values by year
issue_summary <- pm_all %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    total_obs   = n(),
    invalid_obs = sum(pm_invalid),
    prop_invalid = mean(pm_invalid)
  )

print(issue_summary)

ggplot(pm_clean, aes(x = factor(year), y = pm, fill = factor(year))) +
  geom_violin(trim = TRUE, alpha = 0.6) +

  theme_minimal()
##In 2002, the mean PM2.5 concentration was about 16.1 µg/m³, with a median of 12.0.
##In 2022, the mean dropped to 8.4 µg/m³, with a median of 6.8.
##This represents a reduction of nearly 50% over the 20-year span, along with a narrowing spread (lower SD and IQR).
##The violin + boxplots show a clear downward shift in PM2.5 values from 2002 to 2022. The 2022 distribution is tighter, with lower central values, though occasional extreme spikes remain.
##At the state level, air quality in California improved markedly between 2002 and 2022. Central tendencies (mean/median) declined substantially, and typical exposure levels are much lower, reflecting effective pollution control measures and regulations. However, some extreme values in 2022 highlight persistent episodic pollution events.

  select(county, year, mean, median) %>%
